default&#xa0;defaultIntroductiondefault&#xa0;default2
default. 
defaultIn 2010
default the Government made a commitment to give due 
defaultconsideration to the 
defaultUnited Convention on the Rights of the Child (UNCRC) 
defaultwhen making new law and policy
default. 
defaultThe Government must comply with this commitment when shaping 
defaultits policy in respect of legal aid.
default Any 
defaultreform to legal aid must ensure that it respects, protects and fulfils children’s rights. 
defaultCRAE 
defaultis
default concerned that 
defaultthe 
defaultGovernment’s 
defaultproposals 
defaultfor the reform of legal aid 
defaultshow a serious disregard for children’s rights
default.
default&#xa0;
default3. 
defaultLegal aid is central to the rule of law – it ensures accountability in the event that public bodies breach the law, including those laws which 
defaultprotect
default children’s rights, by allowing people 
defaultto 
defaultcomplain to the courts. Legal aid also makes the law effecti
defaultve outside of the court room. It makes it a realistic possibility that people can bring a case when their rights are breached – this possibility encourages public bodies to comply with the law. It is also 
defaultan essential element of a fair justice system
default, ensu
defaultring that it is not only the rich and powerful who can access the courts by providing a vital safety net for those who cannot afford to pay for legal assistance. 
defaultLegal aid is an important aspec
defaultt of the right to a fair trial
default and the right to a remedy
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default4
default. 
defaultChildren’s rights, as enshrined in the law, are meaningless un
defaultless children can take action
default 
defaultwhen their
default rights are 
defaultviolated
default. An effective system of legal aid is crucial to ensuring that children are able to access the court to challenge breaches of their ri
defaultghts. This is recognised by the international human rights bodies. The UN Committee on the Rights of the Child has said:
defaultFor rights to have meaning, effective remedies must be available to redress violations.  This requirement is implicit in the 
default[UNCRC]
default an
defaultd consistently referred to in the other six major international human rights treaties.  Children’s special and dependent status creates real difficulties for them in pursuing remedies for breaches of their rights.  So States need to give particular attenti
defaulton to ensuring that there are effective, child-sensitive procedures available to children and their representatives.  These should 
defaultinclude 
default…
default access to independent complaints procedures and to the courts with necessary legal and other assistance.
